Crimée and Sudetenland, same fight?
BRUXELLES – The Russian takeover of Crimea constitutes the most serious example of aggression in peacetime that Europe has experienced since the annexation of the Sudetenland by Nazi Germany in 1938.
It is certainly now common to downplay the importance of the "Munich lessons" when referring to this episode in which Neville Chamberlain and Édouard Daladier gave in to Hitler's claims over Czechoslovakia in order to appease the Führer.
However, if the Western world were to turn a blind eye to Crimea's annexation – the second case of invasion of a sovereign territory by Russian President Vladimir Putin, following the takeover of the Georgian regions of Abkhazia and South Ossetia in 2008 – current democratic leaders might very well regret their inaction.
Within Western capitals, reactions have so far been mixed.
The sanctions currently under consideration – such as expelling Russia from the G8, for example – could seem humorous if the threat to peace in Europe were not so serious.
Putin considers the collapse of the Soviet Union as the worst catastrophe of modern times, and the man relentlessly strives to revive a fallen Russian empire.
If the West is to be taken seriously, it will have to act with the same determination that Putin demonstrates.
The numerous successes of the Russian president within the framework of his imperialist project have so far cost him almost nothing.
His initiative in favor of an Eurasian Economic Community has allowed Russia to rally a number of resource-rich states, such as Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan, and Turkmenistan.
Georgia was dismembered in 2008.
As for the Armenian government, Russian intimidation has pushed it to reject the association agreement proposed by the European Union.
And here is the most precious strategic trophy – Ukraine – which could well fall into Putin’s hands.
Without Ukraine, Russia « ceases to be an empire, » as explains the former U.S. national security advisor Zbigniew Brzezinski; « on the contrary, strong with a suborned and subordinate Ukraine, Russia automatically becomes an empire again. » And since the majority of Ukrainians do not at all aspire to join Putin’s empire, it is very likely that the country led by the Russian president is now a highly militarized state, a sort of Soviet Union without a Communist Party.
It is essential that the international community’s reaction be up to the level of the adventurism that Putin is displaying.
Canceling summits, proposals for trade agreements, and other participation in as unproductive a forum as the G8 could never be sufficient.
Only actions involving the imposition of tangible economic sanctions, capable of affecting Russian citizens – who, as we recall, keep re-electing Putin to power – could allow us to hope that the Kremlin will abandon its expansionist path.
What kind of sanctions could be involved?
First, Turkey could decide to close the Dardanelles Strait to Russian transport, as it did after the 2008 Russo-Georgian war.
At the time, Turkey had blocked access to the Black Sea in order to prevent the United States from intervening, although it now appears clearly that this was not the intention of the United States.
Aujourd’hui, la Turquie pourrait choisir de fermer les détroits turcs non seulement aux navires de guerre russes, mais également à l’ensemble des paquebots commerciaux faisant route vers les ports russes de la mer Noire.
L’impact sur l’économie de la Russie – de même que sur les prétentions militaires de Poutine – se révélerait considérable.
La Turquie est autorisée à clore les Dardanelles en vertu d’un amendement apporté en 1982 à la Convention de Montreux de 1936.
La Turquie pourrait ainsi retourner contre Poutine le mobile invoqué par celui-ci pour justifier la prise de la Crimée – à savoir qu’il préserverait les ethnies russes y habitant – en affirmant elle-même protéger ses cousins turcs d’appartenance tatare, lesquels, compte tenu des mauvais traitements subis de la part de la Russie, souhaitent clairement demeurer sous règne ukrainien.
Cette semaine, le ministre turc des Affaires étrangères Ahmet Davutoğlu a ordonné à son avion de faire demi-tour en plein ciel, afin de se diriger vers Kiev pour apporter un soutien au nouveau gouvernement par intérim.
Prime Minister Recep Tayyip Erdoğan, who as Putin knows well is not exactly a soft-hearted leader, could thus follow suit by immediately closing the Turkish straits to Russian transport – until Putin recalls all his troops from Crimea so that they can return to their bases, namely those in Sevastopol or in Russia.
It would be good for Turkey to be able to count on the guarantee conferred by Article 5 of the NATO treaty in the event that Russia attempts to intimidate it.
Secondly, President Barack Obama could impose on Russia the same type of financial sanctions that he imposed on Iran around its nuclear program.
These sanctions have indeed significantly undermined the Iranian economy.
In the same way, refusing access to the U.S. financial system for all banks dealing with Russian banks or companies would allow for the creation of an unprecedented economic chaos in Russia since the fall of communism.
Russian citizens must understand that allowing Putin – whose rise to power is based on his promise to end the shortages of the early post-Soviet era – to continue his aggressive imperialist approach could cost them dearly.
Thirdly, Obama could remind the Chinese of their role in the stability of Eurasia.
To Putin, the disintegration of the Soviet Union was a true tragedy, but for China, it represented the most formidable geostrategic opportunity imaginable.
In an instant, an empire that had seized millions of hectares of Chinese territory over the centuries and threatened the People's Republic with nuclear annihilation simply vanished.
Since then, the independent states of Central Asia, and Ukraine itself, have become important trade partners of China.
The Russian invasion of Georgia seriously upset China, as evidenced by the Shanghai Cooperation Organisation summit held after the war (this regional grouping bringing together a number of post-Soviet states with common borders with China and the motherland).
Russia tried to persuade the OCS to recognize the independence of Abkhazia and South Ossetia.
The Organisation nevertheless expressed its disagreement.
However, the Central Asian member states – Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Tajikistan, and Uzbekistan – would never have dared to oppose the Kremlin without China's support.
It is now up to Chinese President Xi Jinping to be less enigmatic in his response to Putin's bold moves.
The real test of this Chinese claim asserting itself as a genuine and responsible protagonist within the international community will indeed take place very soon at the United Nations.
Will China support this blatant violation of international law committed by Putin, or will it stand in support of Ukraine's territorial integrity?
Two other sanction options are also under consideration.
Each Russian leader could thus see their visas rejected or revoked.
It would also be possible to freeze a number of assets, particularly those that have been laundered by oligarchs close to Putin.
Ce n’est que lorsque la douleur sera devenue insupportable, et notamment pour les élites, que pourra échouer cette sorte de kampf que mène aujourd’hui Poutine.
The price of inaction could well turn out to be considerable.
Many countries, from Japan to Israel, count on this promise from America consisting of acting firmly against any serious threat to peace.
Furthermore, when Ukraine gave up its nuclear arsenal in 1994, it did so under the condition that the United States (together with the United Kingdom, France, and Russia) guarantee its territorial integrity.
If Crimea were to remain annexed, no one could blame Ukraine if it decided to renuclearize its defense (which it remains technologically capable of doing).
Lorsque Chamberlain revint de Munich, Winston Churchill s’adressa à lui selon la célèbre formule « Vous aviez le choix entre la guerre et le déshonneur.
Vous avez choisi le déshonneur, et vous aurez la guerre. » Obama et les autres dirigeants occidentaux sont aujourd’hui confrontés à un choix similaire.
S’ils venaient à faire le choix du déshonneur, nous pouvons être certains que l’audacieux Poutine finira tôt ou tard par leur servir une nouvelle guerre.
